#chinatownnyc #sculpture
Photo: @jonprospero

Since I moved within walking distance of NY’s Chinatown a few years ago, I’ve been going there once or twice a week to buy groceries or shop, but really just to take it all in.  I didn’t have a community like this where I grew up, so being able to speak Chinese in shops or buy fresh lychee off the streets still feels miraculous.  But the thing that really strikes me is the sense of comfort and familiarity that hits as soon as I step onto Bayard or Mulberry, like a weight lifted, even though the place still feels new to me.  To give myself an excuse to think about this while cutting up some cardboard, I started this series of figures based on some of the people I see around the neighborhood.  In the 3 weeks or so that it takes to make each figure, I try to distill this vague sense of familiarity down to an expression or gesture that resonates for some reason.  But each figure is also anchored to a specific place and time in the neighborhood, so as I make each one, the interconnected threads between them start to reveal the contours of the larger community.  Despite the fact that I didnt grow up here, I’m finding connections that transcend geography and time.  So, it’s really turned out to be more than just a study, but also a way for me to make this place feel a bit more like home.  Which is why I’m so grateful to be able to share these pieces at Pearl River, a beloved institution that’s at the heart of this community in so many ways.  Looking forward to showing you all what I’ve been working on….

"Did you hear about the new art exhibition at Pearl River?" These lively ladies are part of OUR ROOTS RUN DEEP: Finding Home in Chinatown by @wrnking, which opens tomorrow, Jan. 12 in the Pearl River Mart Gallery. Using only cardboard and glue, Mr. King captures in exquisite beauty and detail everyday moments in nearby Chinatown, through anything-but-ordinary people. 

Come see the works in person from Jan. 12 through April 23 (free and open to the public), and join us for the opening reception on Jan. 12 between 6 and 8 PM. Attendance is free but registration is appreciated. You can find the link in our bio.

Last night @wrnking’s art exhibition, OUR ROOTS RUN DEEP: Finding Home in Chinatown, opened in our SoHo gallery! 🙌 Many thanks to everyone who came out to see Warren’s exquisite cardboard figures in person (and they must be seen in person!) and celebrate with us. We were happy to see familiar faces from the Chinatown, art, and activist communities, as well as new ones who had simply come out for something fun to do 😊

We hope you’ll have the chance to come by too! OUR ROOTS RUN DEEP is on view in our SoHo gallery through April 23. Free and open to the public every day.

Ok… finally recovered a bit from the exhilarating, overwhelming, heartwarming night of the opening.  I’ve been a nerd and introvert much longer than I’ve been an artist, and it’s still hard to get my head around the fact that all of these people are coming to see my stuff.  If you were able to make it out, I can’t thank you enough and I hope we got a chance to chat.  If you weren’t able to make it out, not to worry.. you’ve got until April! 

Thank you (again and again and again!) to @pearlrivermart for the opportunity and all the support.  The best part of all this meeting amazing people and getting new inspiration and ideas.  So now.. back to the studio!

Throwback to 12 years ago when we made a float for the San Francisco Chinese New Years parade.  We made 26 rabbit lanterns by hand, out of wire, plastic wrap, and gauzy stuffing… at my house!! What were we thinking?? But what a great time….

Happy Lunar New Year!

Back to work on this project.  If I post it, it means I’ll stop procrastinating.  Definitely.

Starting for real now.  The earlier sketches allowed for experimentation, but now I’m giving free rein to my perfectionism.  Switched to this archival material, which is much stronger, and will probably be painted or inked later. 

#cardboard #cardboardart #paperart #papercrafts #sculpture #portrait

Still a work in progress, but this is a comparison of how the final figure is going vs the earlier quick sketch using cheap cardboard.  With my process, I have to commit to things pretty early and it’s hard to make adjustments. So doing a quick prototype is useful, because I’m not one of those people who can just “see” it in my head
Getting immersed in precision, craftsmanship.  I really get sucked into this slow, deliberate phase of the process.  Maybe too much.

Still working on this one, but here she is next to the original quick sketch.  I’ll do a few more posts breaking down the main differences.

#cardboard #cardboardart #paperart #papercrafts #wip

A few comments about the differences between the rough sketch and the final version of the figure.. Hands.

Overall, I wanted to simplify the figures a bit more and use broader strokes, because they’re going to be part of a larger composition eventually.  In the legs especially, you can see I’m going pretty minimal— there are large portions that are made of only 2 or 3 surfaces.  But the face and hands carry a lot of the emotional weight, so I kept them fairly detailed.  In the original sketch (second photo), I had one hand grasping the other.  It didn’t quite work for me.  In the final version (the first photo), I actually went with a simpler hand position, but the concave flex in the top fingers, indicating downward pressure, felt more subtle and (I think) had more emotional intensity.

A few comments about the differences between the rough sketch and the final version of the figure.. Torso.

One of the main changes was to the torso, the right side of the coat.  In the sketch version (the brown figure), I broke up the coat into 3 sections, which I highlighted in pink.  Between each section, there’s a strip of shadow, so visually it results in 6 areas of light and dark.  I wanted to keep things simpler, so having this much movement in that area felt too busy and over-complicated.  This figure is going to be just one part of a larger composition, and this many shifts in light and dark could be distracting.

So in the final version (the first photo), I simplified the coat - it only has two sections instead of three.  But then I brought the left arm forward quite a bit more, and tucked the forearm tightly under the belly.  I also changed the shape of the sleeve in order to echo the shapes in the coat, so you have this leaf shape repeated 3 times, in tiers, stepping down from the shoulder to the leg.  It looks a bit like the wing of a bird.  Overall, I think the figure feels more flattened, less cluttered, and just flows a bit better.

A few comments about the differences between the rough sketch and the final version of the figure.. Face. 

With the face, there’s always a balance: If it’s too simplified or abstracted, it feels blank, like a cardboard box.  On the other hand, it if there’s too much detail, something else is lost.  Honestly, I’m not quite sure what it is… Maybe with too much detail, you notice the cardboard too much and it draws attention to the limitations of the material.  Or, maybe, abstracting it leaves room to project your own feelings onto it, making it feel more human or familiar. 

Anyway, with this face, there were two areas that I wanted to push the details a bit more.  The first was in the brow.  This figure is a bit grumpy, and I really wanted to capture a certain beautiful gnarliness in the brows that some people have, that come from a long life of scowling. So you can see in the final version there are a few more contours in the eyebrow area that aren’t in the sketch.  The second was in the area below the nose. (What’s that called?  The wide area above the lips.  There must be a name for it). In the sketch version (second photo), that area is one continuous piece of cardboard.  In the final version, I broke that part into three sections, and offset them slightly, by 2mm or so.  Just a small and subtle addition, but I think it was worth it to give it her a bit more of that pursed-lips expression.

#cardboardart #papercrafting  #sculpture #portrait

Comparing the rough sketch to the final version.  It’s long, but don’t worry, this is the last one.

Some of the surfaces on my figures look flat, but they almost never are.  The parts that seem flat are actually curved first and then flattened out so they retain some curvature.  It bends the light and gives the piece a gradient that makes a big difference.  If I were to leave a section truly flat, it would jump out and you wouldn’t be able to *not* see it.  At least, I can’t. 

Also, I only curve the cardboard in one direction, ever. (Yes, I make a lot of rules for myself). Imagine if, instead of coming as flat sheets, the cardboard came curved into tubes, or cylinders.  You cut shapes out of the cylinders, but you aren’t allowed to bend them any differently.  That’s basically what I’m working with.

So making complicated shapes can be hard, especially rounded ones, and it’s about creating a sense of roundness rather than actual roundness.  One way to do it is to bend a surface.  Another way is to make a curved cut, so that the edge creates roundness.  I usually prefer a combo. 

Take the upper thigh on the sketch version (2nd photo). The thigh is naturally cylindrical, so it seems obvious to bend the cardboard into a tube, which is what I did.  This is an example of using the curved surface to create roundness.  The torso, on the other hand, is made with pieces that are only slightly curved, and the round folds of the fabric come from the shape of the edges.  This is an example of using cuts and edges to show roundness, as opposed to the surface. 

When they’re next to each other on the figure, you can feel the difference, and it was a contrast I didn’t want.  In the final piece (first photo) I changed the upper thigh by rotating the orientation of the curve by about 45 degrees.  I kept the curvature in the surface (shown by the pink swoosh) but now the emphasis is on the edge, the line that runs along the top of the leg that shows the taper down to the knee.  It’s less realistic perhaps, but the shape is more interesting, and I felt it was more consistent with the rest of the piece.  That’s the kind of give-and-take that I think about a lot.

Just beyond humbled and honored to be in the company of all the incredible artists on the list of this year’s recipients and finalists.  Thank you @nyscouncilonthearts and @nyfacurrent for the amazing support and funding! Full details at nyfa.org/blog. #NYSCANYFAFellows

Not cardboard.. it’s my first attempt at clay.  Earlier this year I watched a portrait modeling competition hosted by @nationalsculpturesociety and was completely mesmerized and inspired by all the talented artists.  I’ve never worked with clay, but decided I had to try it, so I signed up for an intro course at @newyorkacademyofart taught by @michelaroman.artist.  Totally hooked after the first class.  Then started watching hours of videos online.  The series by @saypience on Proko was super helpful.. she’s great about articulating her decisions and rationale as she works, and I even made my own tools based on her instructions.  Anyway, I can’t get enough.. I feel like I could spend all day everyday on this.  The process of sculpting with clay vs cardboard is so completely different and I’m excited to see how one informs the other, but that’s down the road.  Right now, I just so badly want to get better at this.

Still in progress, but I need a break.  Going to come back to this one later.
